# Per-file git attributes. Merge drivers for true-append-only files.
#
# runtime-state.jsonl is a true append-only sidecar (record_create_decision
# appends one line per ledger event; no in-place mutation, no status flips).
# The union merge driver keeps BOTH sides' lines on a parallel-PR conflict at
# EOF — safe because there are no line replacements, only adds. This is
# defense in depth for the parallel-async-writer class of conflict the
# `meta-260709T1017Z-parallel-prs-...` finding describes; the manual
# `git merge-file --union` workaround remains the documented operating
# compromise, but this attribute lets the merge succeed automatically when
# the union strategy is sound.
#
# change-log.jsonl is the meta-state change-log stream (Tier 1 split). It is
# true-append-only (writeEntry branches on entry_kind=change-log; the
# core-layer immutability guard in updateEntry/archiveEntry rejects any
# in-place mutation). merge=union resolves the parallel-PR EOF conflict class
# without producing duplicate ids. Plan 260715-0801 Tier 1 Phase 2 step 3.
#
# NOTE: merge=union is a no-op until the union merge driver is configured in
# the clone (git config is per-clone, not committable). Run once per clone:
#   git config merge.union.driver "git merge-file --union %A %O %B"
# Arg order matters: the result MUST land in %A (ours), with %O (ancestor) as
# base and %B (theirs) as other. The widely-cited "git merge-file --union %O
# %A %B" is WRONG — it writes the result to %O and leaves %A unchanged, so git
# silently keeps only "ours" and drops the other side (the data-loss this
# attribute exists to prevent). Verified by the plan's Phase 4 merge=union
# dry-run (two branches from a shared base each appending a change-log at the
# same EOF position). See AGENTS.md §8 for the one-time setup.
#
# meta-state.jsonl is now true append-only (Plan 260716-1101 Tier 2 Phase B
# rewrote the write path to versioned-append via core/registry-append-atomic.js
# + appendRegistryEntryAtomic; mutations append a new versioned line, never
# replace). The read projection (`_readAndParseRegistry` + `registry-table.sh`)
# dedupes to last-wins-by-max-version per id, so `merge=union` is now safe:
# parallel branches that each mutate the same id auto-resolve; both version
# lines are retained in the raw file (audit completeness); the projection
# surfaces the highest-version line. Phase C flip.
runtime-state.jsonl merge=union
change-log.jsonl merge=union
meta-state.jsonl merge=union
